<page_title>An Advanced Technique:  Fluorescent Tags in DNA Chips</page_title>
<text> An Advanced Technique:  Fluorescent Tags in DNA Chips
p. 6 of 6 

An important application of fluorescence is in DNA chips, also called DNA microarrays. A DNA chip is an arrangement of nucleotides with known sequences that have been printed  on a solid surface using a technology such as photolithography. These chips can be used to measure the expression of large number of genes simultaneously.
 
A DNA microarray

Fluorescent tags are attached to single strands of  the DNA sample an investigator wants to understand. The sample is then exposed to known DNA sequences on a chip. They attach to their complements,  and   fluoresce when placed under the light of a scanner. The position of the resulting fluorescence will tell the scientist which genes are there.  The following model schematically illustrates the fluorescence process of tags attached (hybridized) to certain positions in a chip:

 
 
 
 

 
Note: In the above model, we just show a single DNA strand on each address of the array (i.e. each site on the array). In reality, each address can contain many DNA strands of the same sequence.
 

 

